<user_query>
What is the Dispatcher in CoroutineScope function
</user_query>"}]},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A `Dispatcher` in `CoroutineScope` determines **which thread or thread pool** the coroutines will run on. It's part of the `CoroutineContext`.

**Main Dispatchers:**

1. **`Dispatchers.Main`** - UI thread (Android main thread)
2. **`Dispatchers.IO`** - Optimized for I/O operations (file, network, database)
3. **`Dispatchers.Default`** - CPU-intensive work (calculations, data processing)
4. **`Dispatchers.Unconfined`** - Runs in caller thread initially, then resumes in whatever thread the suspending function uses

**In your code:**
```kotlin
val applicationScope = CoroutineScope(SupervisorJob())
```

Since no dispatcher is specified, it uses `Dispatchers.Default` by default.

**Better approach would be:**
```kotlin
val applicationScope = CoroutineScope(SupervisorJob() + Dispatchers.Default)
```

**Example usage:**
```kotlin
// UI updates
launch(Dispatchers.Main) { updateUI() }

// Network call
launch(Dispatchers.IO) { fetchData() }

// Heavy computation
launch(Dispatchers.Default) { processLargeDataset() }
```

The dispatcher ensures your code runs on the appropriate thread for optimal performance and prevents blocking the UI thread."}]}]}
